                <h2>Case 1: Phishing False Positive — Finding the Real Reason Behind the Suspension</h2>
<p>A utility app team's Google Ads account was suddenly suspended during its third week of running ads. The email cited "Circumventing Systems" as the reason. The operations team immediately filed a generic appeal with a simple statement: "Our app is fully compliant, please unban us." The result: no response. Two weeks later, they tried again and were still rejected.</p>
<p><strong>Problem Diagnosis</strong>: The team misidentified the suspension reason. After investigation, they discovered the landing page contained a third-party download link that Google's crawlers flagged as "hiding the true intent through redirects."</p>
<p><strong>Actions Taken</strong>:<br />
1. Immediately modified the landing page, removing all third-party redirects and changing the download button to direct Google Play link<br />
2. Attached screenshots of the updated URL and modification notes to the appeal<br />
3. Added compliance documentation (notarized privacy policy and terms of service)<br />
4. Drafted the appeal letter in English following this structure: Acknowledge + Fix + Promise</p>
<p><strong>Result</strong>: Account reinstated 36 hours after appeal submission, with normal ad delivery resumed.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Case 2: Malware False Positive — Tailor Your Materials to the Specific Issue</h2>
<p>A cross-border e-commerce independent site's ad account was suspended for "Malware or Unwanted Software." After self-inspection, the team found a third-party analytics tracking script embedded in their site code that Google's security scanner flagged as suspicious.</p>
<p><strong>Key Judgment</strong>: The website itself wasn't actually problematic — a third-party script triggered the security review. Such cases have higher appeal success rates, provided you can demonstrate your site's actual security.</p>
<p><strong>Actions Taken</strong>:<br />
1. Ran the site through Google Safe Browsing Lookup tool and captured screenshots<br />
2. Contacted the third-party analytics platform for their security certification<br />
3. Hired the tech team to conduct a full site security audit and obtain a clean malware report<br />
4. Detailed in the "Additional Information" field: which script, which time period, and why it has now been cleaned up</p>
<p><strong>Result</strong>: Approved on first appeal, account reinstated within 48 hours.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Case 3: Trademark Infringement — Incomplete Materials Lead to Repeated Rejections</h2>
<p>A consumer goods brand used competitor brand keywords as negative keywords in their search campaigns, but their ad copy was reported by the competitor for "Trademark Infringement." After the account suspension, the operations team submitted their business license and a self-declaration form, thinking that would be sufficient.</p>
<p><strong>Problem Breakdown</strong>: Trademark infringement appeals require a complete chain of authorization or proof of legitimate use. A business license alone cannot prove the right to use the trademark.</p>
<p><strong>Actions Taken</strong>:<br />
1. First removed all creative text and keywords involving the trademark<br />
2. Prepared authorization documents (if an agent) or trademark registration certificates (for own brands)<br />
3. Drafted a formal rectification commitment letter stating deleted content and promising no future use<br />
4. Attached the brand's official website as evidence of brand authenticity</p>
<p><strong>Result</strong>: Approved on second appeal, account reinstated with a 90-day probation period requiring strict adherence to Google Ads policies.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Appeal Materials Checklist: Ensuring One-Time Approval</h2>
<p>Based on the three cases above, here's the universal structure for effective appeal materials:</p>
<h3>Basic Information Layer</h3>
<ul>
<li>Google Ads Customer ID (required, 11 digits)</li>
<li>Affected campaign or URL (specific to the URL level)</li>
<li>Appeal submission time (keep records for follow-ups)</li>
</ul>
<h3>Factual Explanation Layer</h3>
<ul>
<li>Clearly state which policy violation you understand</li>
<li>Explain the specific reason for the violation (not vague generalizations)</li>
<li>List the time period when the violation occurred</li>
</ul>
<h3>Rectification Proof Layer</h3>
<ul>
<li>Screenshots or documentation of implemented changes</li>
<li>Upcoming modification plans with estimated completion times</li>
<li>Third-party security reports (if applicable)</li>
</ul>
<h3>Assurance and Commitment Layer</h3>
<ul>
<li>Commit to how you'll prevent similar violations going forward</li>
<li>Can attach account structure optimization plans (to demonstrate compliance sincerity)</li>
</ul>
<hr />
<h2>Three Golden Rules for Submitting Appeals</h2>
<p><strong>Rule 1: Fix First, Appeal Second</strong><br />
Don't appeal while keeping the violating content. Google's review team will recheck your site and ads. If they find unfixed violations, rejection is guaranteed.</p>
<p><strong>Rule 2: Materials Must Close the Loop</strong><br />
Every violation charge needs a corresponding response with supporting evidence. Flagged for "Misrepresentation"? Then provide authentic product photos, user review screenshots, etc.</p>
<p><strong>Rule 3: Be Precise with Language</strong><br />
Submit appeals in English where possible and provide as much detail as the form allows. Vague statements like "Please give me another chance" won't increase approval rates.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Final Takeaway</h2>
<p>Account suspension isn't the end, but repeated failed appeals will seriously delay your campaign timeline. If you've tried twice without success, pause self-appeals — frequent rejections push accounts into deeper review queues. At this point, contacting Google Ads official support or professional account management services is often more effective than continuing to try on your own.</p>
